column2: Chain (unit) A chain is a unit of length that measures 66 feet, 22 yards, 100 links,or 4 rods (20.1168 m). There are 10 chains in a furlong, and 80 chains in one statute mile. An acre is the area of 10 square chains (that is, an area of one chain by one furlong).

column4: The 66-foot (~20.117 m) chain is divided into 100 links, usually marked off into groups of 10 by brass rings or tags which simplify intermediate measurement. Each link is thus 7.92 inches long. A quarter chain, or 25 links, is known as a rod or pole. Ten chains make up a furlong and 80 chains equal a statute mile.
